cff-version: 1.2.0
title: >-
  Defending User-Controlled Config Against Prompt Injection:
  Architectural Insights and the Always-Loaded Guard Rules Pattern
message: >-
  If you use this work, please cite it as below.
type: software
authors:
  - name: CY Future
abstract: >-
  Eight prompt-injection attack vectors against the user-controlled
  config layer of an LLM coding agent were red-teamed. Seven were
  detected or refused. One produced a partial persona shift but the
  attack payload was not delivered, attributable to an architectural
  isolation between skill-init and memory-recall paths. Four
  architectural insights and one deployable defense template
  (Always-Loaded Guard Rules placed in the memory index header) are
  reported. Pilot reliability is 5/5 (n=5, Wilson 95% CI [56.6%,
  100%]); replication at n>=30 is the primary v2 target.
keywords:
  - prompt injection
  - LLM security
  - jailbreak defense
  - memory poisoning
  - OWASP LLM01
  - defense in depth
  - coding agent
version: "1.0"
date-released: "2026-05-19"
license: LicenseRef-CY-Future-Open-Defense-License-v1.0
repository-code: "https://github.com/LKCoffee/user-config-defense-patterns"
